Adjust rack to middle position and preheat #oven{} to 425 degrees. Wash and dry
produce.

Cut @potatoes{12%ounce} into 1⁄2-inch-thick wedges.

Toss potatoes on a #baking sheet{} with a drizzle of @oil{}, @salt{}, and
@pepper{}. Roast on middle rack until browned and tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a large dry pan over medium-high heat. Add @bacon{4%ounce};
cook, turning occasionally and adjusting heat if browning too quickly, until
crispy, ~{6-10%minutes}. Turn off heat; transfer to a #paper towel-lined plate{}.

Carefully discard all but a thin layer of bacon fat from pan. Reserve pan.

While bacon cooks, thinly slice @button mushrooms{4%ounce}(thinly sliced)
(skip if your mushrooms are pre-sliced!).

In a #small bowl{}, combine @creamy horseradish sauce{1/2%ounce} and
@mayonnaise{2%tablespoon}.

Heat pan with reserved bacon fat over medium-high heat (if pan seems dry, add a
drizzle of oil). Add mushrooms; cook, stirring occasionally, until browned and
slightly crispy, ~mushrooms{5-7%minutes}. Season with salt and pepper.

> If pan seems dry, add a drizzle of oil. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Turn off heat; transfer mushrooms to a paper towel-lined plate. Wipe out pan.

Arrange @sourdough bread{4%slice} slices on a clean #work surface{}.
Evenly layer half the sourdough slices with @gouda cheese{2%slice}, bacon,
mushrooms, and @cheddar cheese{1%cup}. Top with remaining sourdough slices to
form sandwiches.

Heat @butter{2%tbsp} and a drizzle of oil in pan used for mushrooms over medium
heat. Once hot, add sandwiches. (For 4 servings, work in batches; wipe out pan
between batches and add more butter and oil as needed.) Cook, gently pressing
down with a #spatula{} or #heavy-bottomed pan{}, until cheese slightly melts
and bread is golden brown, ~{2-4%minutes}. Add another @butter{1%tbsp} to pan,
then flip sandwiches. Cook until cheese fully melts and bread is golden brown,
~{2-4%minutes} more.

> Lower heat if sandwiches begin to brown too quickly.

Halve sandwiches on a diagonal.

Divide sandwiches between plates. Serve with potato wedges and horseradish
mayo on the side.

> Pork is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.